(c) Too sparing use of elision. In Vergil's hands elision³ vas a powersul rhythmic appliance: by it he was able to load or roughen lines or parts os lines so as to regulate the move- ment; and thus he makes sound and sense agree. In this respect Lucan’s rhythm⁴ is decidedly weak. (d) Want os variety in the endings of lines. The spondaic ending occurs in the Pharsalia sourteen⁵ times only, and in eleven of these sourteen cases the last word is either a Greek word or a proper name or both. Still the number of such endings would not seem so very small were it not that the spondaic is almost the only abnormal ending employed by Lucan There are only two⁸ other cases of variation and the last word is Greek in both cases.
